"(https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:234
msgid "Prior art"
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:237
msgid ""
"As the \"Credits & License\" says, the main inspiration for the proposed "
"policy is the [Acceptable Use Policy](https://pypi.org/policy/acceptable-use-"
"policy/) of the Python Package Index (PyPI). Their policy in turn is based "
"on the [Acceptable Use Policies](https://docs.github.com/en/site-policy/"
"acceptable-use-policies/) of GitHub. Both of these policies are licensed "
"under the [Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license](https://"
"creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/), so we can happily reuse them."
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:239
msgid ""
"[PEP 541](https://peps.python.org/pep-0541/) (Python Enhancement Proposal) "
"was also mixed into the document above, specifically the [Invalid Projects]"
"(https://peps.python.org/pep-0541/#invalid-projects) section."
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:241
msgid ""
"The third source of material are the \"[Open-Source Terms](https://docs."
"npmjs.com/policies/open-source-terms)\" from npm, from which a few more "
"rules on \"Acceptable Content\" were imported."
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:243
msgid ""
"RubyGems, Maven Central, Packagist (PHP) and Nuget (C#) were also "
"investigated, but they did not appear to have written rules published in "
"easy-to-find places."
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:246
msgid "Unresolved questions"
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:249
msgid ""
"Is the wording of the \"name reservation\" clause sufficient to discourage "
"name squatting in the future?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:250
msgid ""
"Are there any current legitimate uses of crates.io that would suddenly be "
"forbidden by these new rules?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:251
msgid ""
"Should the crates.io policies forbid embedding executable binaries in the "
"crate files?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:253
msgid "Future possibilities"
msgstr ""

#: src/3463-crates-io-policy-update.md:256
msgid ""
"[PEP 541](https://peps.python.org/pep-0541/) also defines rules for "
"abandoned projects and how people could continue maintenance for them. "
"Introducing something like that would be a large deviation for crates.io "
"though, and something that would need a dedicated RFC. Nevertheless, it is "
"worth thinking about if the majority of the Rust community would prefer "
"having such a ruleset."
msgstr ""
